pinned_questions.body: Did Pharrell Williams have anything to do with the production of this song?

body.html: When Pharrell is featured on a song, it is because of production. This is the exemption, however. Daft Punk does recognize The Neptunes as an inspiration, but Pharrell was used in “Get Lucky” and “Lose Yourself to Dance” as a voice of one of the greatest producers of modern times that could provide real soul vocals, rather than production, to Daft Punk’s throwback project.

body.html:
In Greek mythology, the phoenix is a fiery bird that cyclically undergoes life and death, burning into ashes at old age, leaving behind a young chick.

Pharrell mentioned this legend in his book Places and Spaces I’ve Been; on his career and creative process:

I like using the allegory of the phoenix to describe how my work evolves. The bird sets itself on fire… and in the embers is an egg. What I’m saying is that in order to do great things, you must be unafraid to detach yourself from where you think you’ve had some interesting success, because you’ve got to recreate yourself again and you can’t do that holding to a glory from yesterday. You’ve got to continue to reinvent yourself today, all the while thinking about tomorrow.

Daft Punk’s first album, Homework, includes a track called “Phoenix.” Around the time it was released, Laurent Brancowitz, who’d been in an earlier band with Daft Punk called Darlin' adopted the name for his next band. If the earlier band had never dissolved or “burned into ashes,” we might never have had these two great bands.

Pharrell may have (un)intentionally teased this lyric in an interview with Nardwuar from 2013’s SXSW:

body.markdown:
In Greek mythology, the phoenix is a fiery bird that cyclically undergoes life and death, burning into ashes at old age, leaving behind a young chick.

http://images.rapgenius.com/a7773099e4dc1f07e92a58a595ff7f47.1000x625x1.jpg

Pharrell mentioned this legend in his book [*Places and Spaces I've Been*](http://www.amazon.com/Pharrell-Places-Spaces-Ive-Been/dp/0847835898); on his career and creative process: 

> I like using the allegory of the phoenix to describe how my work evolves. The bird sets itself on fire… and in the embers is an egg. What I’m saying is that in order to do great things, you must be unafraid to detach yourself from where you think you’ve had some interesting success, because you’ve got to recreate yourself again and you can’t do that holding to a glory from yesterday. You’ve got to continue to reinvent yourself today, all the while thinking about tomorrow.

Daft Punk's first album, [Homework](/albums/Daft-punk/Homework), includes a track called ["Phoenix."](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wxBc6JjKSWU) Around the time it was released, [Laurent Brancowitz](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_Brancowitz), who'd been in an earlier band with Daft Punk called [Darlin'](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darlin_%28band%29) adopted the name for his [next band](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix_%28band%29). If the earlier band had never dissolved or "burned into ashes," we might never have had these two great bands.

Pharrell may have (un)intentionally teased this lyric in an interview with Nardwuar from 2013's SXSW:

https://youtu.be/p4_ygYqPu7E?t=10m36s

user.about_me_summary:
Leaving Genius at the end of the year

These numbers don’t matter, y'all. That number right next to my name? Irrelevant. It does not matter how much IQ you have or how many upvotes your annotation got, how many of your annotations were featured in articles or how high your transcription made it on the charts.

These virtual points are not correlated to your real life worth and value. Remember that.

I do this to write transcending experiences for curious music fans who are intrigued about the deeper meaning(s).

Unapologetically honest

Yes, right here
